REVENANT SLEUTH — CHARACTER BIBLE v1.0 (Chapters 1–11)
Canon / Style Locks
POV: Detective Adrian Kane, first-person.
Tense: Past tense.
Tone: Noir detective + urban horror + occult conspiracy.
Reveal discipline: Full truth (Lich Lord, essence source, Max resurrected it) not explicit until Ch. 11 (or end of Ch. 10 at earliest).
Recurring signatures (foreshadow only):
Heat theft / unnatural cold
Obedience reflex to bass/rhythm
Reassembly/stitched bodies
Mirrors/one-way watching
Archaic “court/fealty/tribute” language drift

1) Detective ADRIAN KANE — Protagonist
Snapshot
Role: Homicide / Major Crimes detective.
Archetype: Noir crusader with compromised hands.
Baseline vibe: Observational, controlled menace, relentless.
Core Wound / Need / Fear / Lie
Wound: Collapse of partnership with Max (ex-partner)—betrayal plus guilt (Kane missed it, enabled it, or failed to stop it).
Need: Moral agency without pretending purity; to choose the right line to cross.
Fear: Loss of selfhood (becoming a tool, a puppet, a slave).
Lie (early): “Willpower and violence can solve anything.”
Strengths
Excellent pattern recognition at scenes.
Strong street instincts; reads predators well.
Willingness to act under uncertainty.
Credibility inside the department (reputation, results).
Flaws
Uses intimidation/violence as default lever.
Control issues; slow to ask for help.
Obsessive focus; risks tunnel vision.
Emotional repression; sleeps poorly, isolates.
Signature Tells (repeatable on-page)
Checks exits first, faces second.
Anger = quieter voice, smaller movements.
Hands busy (weapon check, sleeve roll, tapping file edge).
Uses last names to distance; first names when it matters.
Ethical Line Progression (arc lever)
Ch 1–2: Crosses lines impulsively (Tony).
Ch 5–6: Leans into investigation; restraint grows.
Ch 9–11: Crosses lines strategically, with purpose and cost.
Secrets
Knows Max’s habits, tells, and “message style.”
Has at least one old case file that’s compromised/unfinished (Max-era).
Does not know the Lich truth early—only that the drug is “alive/wrong.”
Emotional Track by Chapter Range
Ch 1–2: Horror → anger → obsession; chooses partnership (Evelyn).
Ch 3–4: Protective control → rescue rage → first dread of “systemic control.”
Ch 5–6: Investigator mode returns; guilt surfaces (Max); fear of contamination begins.
Ch 7–8: War footing; institution pressure; fights to keep badge and truth.
Ch 9–11: Pattern clarity; accepts real enemy; final confrontation; vindication.
End State (Book 1)
Still a detective (vindicated), changed worldview.
Opens to connection (Evelyn).
Accepts that evil can be contained, not “solved.”

2) Evelyn SINCLAIR — Partner / Deuteragonist
Snapshot
Role: Former Internal Affairs investigator; now private investigator/contractor.
Archetype: Controlled operator with buried conscience.
Baseline vibe: Elegant steel; calm; doesn’t posture.
Core Wound / Need / Fear / Lie
Wound: A witness died due to departmental/political stalling and suppression.
Need: Agency; to act before institutions bury truth again.
Fear: Being controlled/owned (direct thematic mirror of slavery mechanism).
Lie (early): “Attachment is weakness.”
Strengths
Power-structure intuition (who benefits, who blocks).
Social camouflage (high-end and street).
Efficient violence (last resort, quick).
Planning and contingency thinking.
Flaws
Withholds information to maintain leverage.
Slow to emotionally commit; tests allies.
Can go ruthlessly pragmatic when triggered by institutional corruption.
Signature Tells
Holds eye contact longer than comfortable.
Posture remains composed even when hurt.
Economizes motion; checks comms/exits/hands in ritual sequence.
Exposure Consequence (ongoing tool + threat)
After Chapter 4:
Sensitivity to markings (pressure/vertigo).
Notices bass patterns others ignore.
Involuntary tension on command-like rhythm hits. This escalates subtly across Ch 5–9; becomes instrumental late-book.
Secrets (timed release)
Withholds full witness story until trust moment (ideal: Ch 5–6 quiet scene).
Has partial knowledge of symbol history (not source truth).
May have a file on Kane/Max (enough to suspect, not enough to solve).
End State (Book 1)
Chooses trust intentionally (Kane).
Moves from “survive alone” to “fight with someone.”
Vacation epilogue: earned softness, not naïve.

3) Max — Primary Human Antagonist / Tragic Ex-Partner
Snapshot
Role: Kane’s ex-partner; now occult-connected kingpin/strategist.
Archetype: Fallen cop + visionary criminal + puppet who thinks he’s king.
Baseline vibe: Intimate menace; knows Kane.
Core Wound / Need / Fear / Lie
Wound: Past powerlessness/resentment (law, criminals, humiliation, failure).
Need: Absolute control and significance.
Fear (hidden): Being commanded; being irrelevant.
Lie: “I command death; therefore nothing commands me.”
Surface Goal (what Max believes)
Use drug trade + “gifted essence” to become untouchable and powerful.
Humiliate Kane; prove superiority.
True Function (unknown to Max until late)
Distribute essence widely enough to seed a controllable army.
Signature Tells
Speaks like he’s addressing an audience.
Uses Kane’s name slowly, deliberately.
Occasional archaic diction (“tribute,” “court,” “fealty”).
Private pauses as if listening—never explained early.
End State (Book 1 options; choose during drafting)
Tragic collapse: realizes he was used, breaks.
Horror escalation: becomes partially “claimed” (future threat).
Escape: vanishes with consequences in motion.
(You can decide final outcome when plotting Ch 11 scene order.)

4) Voss — Secondary Antagonist / Frontman Node
Snapshot
Role: Velvet Abyss owner; distribution/ritual architecture caretaker.
Archetype: Velvet-gloved predator; ambitious subordinate.
Baseline vibe: Slippery, theatrical, irritated when control is constrained.
Psychology
Need: Status, wealth, dominion.
Fear: Being replaced/consumed by higher power.
Conflict: Thinks he’s running it; actually servicing it.
Behavioral Rules
Delegates violence; uses leverage and surveillance.
Anger appears as restraint and tightening nets—not tantrums.
“Lets Kane go” against his preference (reader never told why).
End State (Book 1)
Discarded/punished or escapes stripped—serves as warning about serving darker kings.

5) The Lich Lord — True Antagonist (Unnamed until reveal)
Snapshot
Role: Ancient necromantic intelligence; source of “essence.”
Archetype: Patient monarch of death; infrastructural strategist.
Presence: Mostly indirect—through signatures.
Signatures (consistency rules)
Heat theft around vials/lockers/wounds
Obedience reflex to bass/rhythm
Reassembly (stitching, arranging)
Mirror watching (reflections show extra truth)
Aristocratic patience (events feel “scheduled”)
Goal
Create an obedient army through distributed essence + activation architecture.

